### Findings

#### 1. Enum.ToString() allocates via reflection on every call (1 instance)
**Severity:** 🔴 Critical
**Impact:** `Enum.ToString()` uses reflection and allocates a string on every invocation. Combined with `.ToLowerInvariant()` allocating a second string, this produces **2 heap allocations per time unit per log entry** — potentially millions/min.
**File:** `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L175`
**Fix:** Cache lowercase unit names in a static array indexed by enum value.
```csharp
// Before
var unitName = unit.ToString().ToLowerInvariant();
return value == 1 ? $"{value} {unitName}" : $"{value} {unitName}s";

// After
private static readonly string[] s_unitNames =
    ["year", "month", "week", "day", "hour", "minute", "second", "millisecond"];
private static readonly string[] s_unitNamesPlural =
    ["years", "months", "weeks", "days", "hours", "minutes", "seconds", "milliseconds"];

private static string FormatTimePart(int value, TimeUnit unit, CultureInfo culture) =>
    $"{value} {(value == 1 ? s_unitNames[(int)unit] : s_unitNamesPlural[(int)unit])}";
```

#### 2. LINQ chains on hot path (16 operator calls across 5 methods)
**Severity:** 🔴 Critical
**Impact:** Each LINQ operator (`.Where`, `.Select`, `.Take`, `.Any`, `.Aggregate`) allocates an enumerator object and a delegate. Across the `Humanize` call chain, a single invocation triggers **5-8 enumerator + delegate allocations** before producing a result. At millions of calls/min, this is significant GC pressure.
**Files:** `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L128, L140, L143, L146, L149, L158, L169, L244, L261-262, L270-272, L284, L304`
**Fix:** Replace LINQ chains with `foreach` loops or index-based iteration. The data is always a small `List<string?>` (≤8 items) — a simple loop is both faster and more readable.
```csharp
// Before (L127-128) — allocates enumerator + delegate
private static bool IsContainingOnlyNullValue(IEnumerable<string?> timeParts) =>
    !timeParts.Any(x => x != null);

// After — zero allocation
private static bool IsContainingOnlyNullValue(List<string?> timeParts)
{
    foreach (var part in timeParts)
        if (part != null) return false;
    return true;
}
```
```csharp
// Before (L133-149) — 3 enumerator allocations + list materialization
private static List<string?> SetPrecisionOfTimeSpan(
    IEnumerable<string?> timeParts, int precision, bool countEmptyUnits)
{
    if (!countEmptyUnits)
        timeParts = timeParts.Where(x => x != null);
    timeParts = timeParts.Take(precision);
    if (countEmptyUnits)
        timeParts = timeParts.Where(x => x != null);
    return [.. timeParts];
}

// After — single pass, zero LINQ allocation
private static List<string?> SetPrecisionOfTimeSpan(
    List<string?> timeParts, int precision, bool countEmptyUnits)
{
    var result = new List<string?>(precision);
    int taken = 0;
    foreach (var part in timeParts)
    {
        if (taken >= precision) break;
        if (countEmptyUnits) taken++;
        if (part != null)
        {
            if (!countEmptyUnits) taken++;
            result.Add(part);
        }
    }
    return result;
}
```

#### 3. `.Select().Where().ToArray()` in collection formatter (3 operator instances)
**Severity:** 🔴 Critical
**Impact:** `HumanizeDisplayStrings` (L269-272) allocates 2 enumerators + 2 delegates + a final `string[]` array on every call. Called from every `Humanize<T>` overload.
**File:** `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L269-272`
**Fix:** Replace with a single `foreach` loop that filters and trims into a pre-sized list.
```csharp
// Before
var itemsArray = strings
    .Select(item => item == null ? string.Empty : item.Trim())
    .Where(item => !string.IsNullOrWhiteSpace(item))
    .ToArray();

// After
var items = new List<string>();
foreach (var item in strings)
{
    if (item == null) continue;
    var trimmed = item.Trim();
    if (trimmed.Length > 0) items.Add(trimmed);
}
```

